                        <seg type="rubrication">Nomina sacra; names of the categories of melody and
                           their abbreviations (ʿǝzl, gǝʿǝz, ʾararay); elements of punctuation
                           signs; Ethiopic numerals or their elements. 
 Text I-1
 Two
                           initial lines on the incipit page; names of feasts and other occasions;
                           names of antiphons and chants, and their abbreviations (e.g., mazmur,
                           salām, ʾaryām, mǝlṭān, qǝne); initial words of supplications, antiphons
                           and other chants, and their sections (e.g., nastäbqʷǝʿ, ʾaṣmǝʿ,
                           täśahalänni, nǝsebbǝḥo, ʾantä, täkäśtä, sǝmǝʿanni); intratextual musical
                           notation signs (e.g.,ʿabiy zema); the word haleluya.
 Text II
                           Names of sections sometimes followed by feast names and initial lines
                           (e.g., wāzemā za-ʾabuna ʾAragāwi); names of antiphons and their
                           abbreviations (e.g., maḫǝlet, mazmur, śalast, salām, ba-5-tu, ʾabun,
                           ʾaryām, ʾǝsma la-ʿālam, kʷǝllǝkkǝmu, za-ʾamlākiya, za-yǝʾǝze, yǝtbārak);
                           names of other chants and their abbreviations (e.g., mǝlṭān, mǝsbak,
                           mǝqnāy, mǝdgam, ʿǝzl, qǝne); musical notation signs: intratextual (e.g.,
                           qāla ʿawadi, ʾaklilä, täsäfḥa, ba-zemahu) and marginal (entire and
                           elements); elements of the Table of halleluiatic chants; tamallas signs
                           (fols. 30va l.16); crude frames or lines used for indicating festive
                           periods (e.g., fols. 38vb-39rb).</seg>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
